This is a project rifle that I'm selling since I have a few too many projects going on. This is considered a project rifle because I believe the headspace to be a little over what I would normally like. It does NOT close on a field gauge but will on a no-go gauge meaning it's most likely safe but I would get it checked out by a smith if you are not capable of checking yourself.

Not pictured are the new stainless action screws that I put in to replace the ones that were there when I took these photos.

Trigger would cost you $155 new, barrel around 300. This is an excellent price on nice rifle to build from or just set the headspace and go varmint hunting.

postcontent: Para-Military 2Why change something if it works? Because, at Spyderco, they practice the principle of C.Q.I. - Constant Quality Improvement. If they can refine and improve the ergonomics or cutting performance of an established model, they do it. Their 2010 Para-Military 2 has several changes over the classic version. The G-10 handle is narrowed at the end improving the ergonomics. The handle and blade have been profiled thinner; removing uncomfortable angles when in the closed position. It features a Compression Lock and an ambidextrous-friendly four way clip which carries tip-up/tip-down, left/right-hand and rests deeper in a pocket. They kept the same high-performance CPM-S30V full flat-ground blade but they've also lengthened the blade's tip and added additional surface jimping to both the spine and finger choil. Implementation of a new Bushing Pivot System generates fluid action and more consistent manufacturing tolerances. Larger lanyard gives more options for carry. Refinements to overall construction may not be drastic or even visible to the eye but from the G-10 textured handle to the CPM-S30V steel full flat blade, everything is sharper, smoother and guaranteed to provide performance and user comfort. title: For Sale/Trade:  36" Sneaky Bag - Rifle Bag
postcontent:
The Covert Rifle Bag was designed at the request of armed professionals who were looking for the most discreet way to transport a ready to use weapons system in some of the worlds most dangerous environments where the consequences of being discovered would be dire. 
There are only so many ways to hide an object with a fixed set of dimensions. Change the object or use a version of camoflage that  tricks the mind into thinking the object is something else.  With external bungees and daisy chain  for securing non gun items, rounded edges and designed to be carried over the shoulder like a quiver or backpack the CRB blends into enviornments where a traditional squared off discreet case might get "Made" more easily.  The CRB  looks enough like a sports equipment bag or hiking backpack that it does not immediately scream "Gun Inside Here"  to bystanders.  We think we struck a nice balance here because you do not need tp dissasemble your loaded weapons, making them faster to get into action while also having a profile that gives you extra time if you are under scrutiny in a denied area.
The internal weapons compartment is slick, with no ties or dangling things to facilitate a speedy weapons  removal from the bag, even with magazines and optics attached.
There is a plastic insert at the bottom of the bag so that sharp muzzle devices do not poke through the bag, when weapons are carried muzzle down or set on hard surfaces with the muzzle facing down.  There is now also an internal padded divider to facilitate carry of more than one weapon, broken down weapon systems or other tools. The main compartment utilizes a lockable YKK zipper to secure contents and to allow the CRB to function as a lockable container in those areas or agencies that require it.
There is a main external storage  pocket with MOLLE/Velcro grid inside should you want to attach other pockets, pouches or holsters. In addition to the main external storage pocket, there is a concealed "Flat" pocket suitable for paperwork or other items as well as a small "Key Pocket" that is sized to fit keys and most smart phones.
Many users report this external pocket (10" x 10" x 1.5") is the perfect size for a small active shooter bag and trauma kit, allowing you to have a small fighting load with your primary weapon. 
The long and thin overall profile lends the bag to being attached behind car seats without being too obtrusive while still giving quick access to the bag contents.
Comes in two sizes to fit most popular weapons in use (31" x 12" x 2" and 36" x 12" x 2") the CRB's were designed to be slung over the shoulder "Quiver"  style but can also be carried "Backpack"  fashion with a simple re-routing of the shoulder strap.
Features:
Made of 1000D nylon
Milspec webbings and bungees
Removable closed cell foam and HDPE plastic. The CRB will protect the contents inside and keep you from getting jabbed by sharp charging handles or other accessories.
MOLLE/Velcro grid in the extermal pocket which accepts all MOLLE compatible accessories on the market. We like the ones we make but any other manufacturers product should do fine as well.
Dimensions 36" x 12" x 2" (4" where the external pocket is).
In the 36" overall length CRB, we have seen the folowing Weapon Systems fit with magazine inserted and an optic attached:
AR15/M16 Family of weapons with an overall length (Non Colapsed or fixed) of less than 36 inches.
AK family of weapons with fixed stocks.
Some Shotguns with 18 inch barrels and shorter stocks or folding stocks.
Youtube Video by Sneaky Bags

title: For Sale:  Savage Model 99 EG 300 Savage - Beautiful Gun!!!!
postcontent:
This is one of the nicest and best shooting 99 savages that I have ever shot.  This gun is in the hard hitting 300 savage.  It routinely shoots 1" groupings for me at 50 yards and is in extremely nice shape for a gun of its age.  The serial number on the gun dates it to a 1950 date of manufacturing.  The gun is NOT drilled and tapped for a scope.  This was one of the last model years that Savage did not drill and tap these guns.  It is getting to be tough to find one in this shape that has not been drilled and tapped.  The blueing is still very nice on this gun and the lever case coloring is also very nice.  The wood on this gun shows a few hunting scrapes, but not any large dings or gouges.  It is a good honest savage 99 survivor.  

Good thing about the 300 Savages, you can go down the road to gander mountain and still buy shells for this cartridge.  It is very similar ballistically to a 308 winchester.

I have lowered my price to $575 on this rifle, can't go much lower on this one.  It is worth every penny of that and would be a nice addition to anyone's collection. Please call or text REDACTED if you are interested or send an email to me.
